snippet.textDisplay:
We should throw equations like this at student's. Are we adults so arrogant that we don't think some will understand these equations. Of course some will. That's why we are not producing science based students out of high school. This is what happens to students that can take it, but no one throws it at them. My grandson is 17 and does nothing but gaming and sleeping, he is in no way prepared for life and that's ashame because he was never challenged in school or by his parents. I did as much as I could as grandpa and through equations at him at a very young age. At the age of 8 I was teaching algebra to him as fast as I could, he stumbled a little but he kept taking it in, he understood the concepts...smart kid with no guidance. In high school the physics teach could not keep up with his knowledge intake and surpassed the teachers ability so they did nothing! He stay bored while other had to work harder at understanding the material. It was sad to watch my grandson go through this. I continued to do my best at teaching him the uses for equations in my garage, in aviation, pyrotechnics, electronics, etc.. it was amazing how fast he could not only learn mechanical things but abstract concepts as well. Before long he was throwing me theorys about black holes, space/time, and quantum mechanics. Blowing me away with drawings and his insight. Scary. Academia has to make a place for these students. Teachers are not trained how to spot and work with these students that understand concept like the one your showing us. It's a big gap in public schools. This is what I did with all my students, I immersed them in algebra through hands on applications,
building projects such as the ones I tough my grandson and then tought how equations would predict behavior, movement, trajectory, so on. There was always a handful of students that understood, I could go on and on. I guess my point is yes we need to throw equations like this at students as early as "they" can learn it. Thanks for the video.

snippet.textDisplay:
So, what we are talking about is a formula that describes the wobble in any dynamically balanced system? That seems to be the common denominator of all systems you describe. It's a beautifull find and I had never heard about the feigenbaum constant before, so thank you for that. Also love the graphics on the Mandelbrot!
I agree education should acknowledge the existence of open questions. There is a BIG caveat though. I'd rather it be done without the use of the words like "spooky" or "miracle" or trying to attach some other arbitrary value to the fact that a question is open and the significance of this is unknown.
Most curently open questions may seem trivial at first. Until recently the drying of coffeestains was a mystery and I only figured out last week how a giraffe might get a near perfect voronoi distribution in it's spots by using only a cellular automaton (which seems the most logical way for a giraffe). This one regularly kept me awake for the last 5 years. Usually the open questions describe some principle that can be used elsewhere, which makes them almost all significant and usually nobody seems to care about them much. Just skip over them.
So I feel the average student (or person) will be much more triggered by any qualification of an open question, than by the question itself. This leads to all forms of magical thinking.
Magical thinking happens to all of us..
For a full half hour I followed a kind of mathematical intuition, that a natural ratio for frequencies doubling like Feigenbaums constant should be easily found by an elegant expression using the constants PI, e and Phi....
And there are a few variations I tried that came remarkably close: Phi^PI=4.53 and (1+PI-e) ^ (Phi+e) = 4.62 for instance. (PI^e)/ (Phi+PI) =4.7 is another one. They seem to dance around that value. But you have to want to see it.. And then I remembered, that's the way madness lies :)

snippet.textDisplay:
Think about the graph of sin(1/x) near x=0. Moving toward zero, you can only predict where the function will go for so long. Then the time scale changes drastically. That’s where the chaotic behavior is. You can always shrink your time scale, then you can see what the function looks like again, but if you keep moving closer to x=0, you’ll find that the function’s time scale keeps shrinking also, so much that it appears chaotic again. If you skip past all of it and just move to x=0, you’ll have no idea what the curve looked like as you “passed over” it. It is all a mess!

Also think about what it looks like to leave zero. Any small adjustment off of zero leads you to some unpredictable value of the function. Maybe divide that adjustment by two, then what is the function value? You can only know what’s going to be there by going there. You can’t really predict it, you just have to observe it to know what’s there. This is chaos, and it’s really awesome!

snippet.textDisplay:
Plz do a video going further into Chaos Theory. James Gleick's Chaos was an eye-opening book for me as well.

Most people don't realize Chaos Theory was born, in part, from an attempt at long range weather prediction, nor that it puts to the grave the idea that we can calculate what our climate will do in the far future. If this is a shock to you, dear reader, don't get defensive and scream "climate and weather are different things!" as if that changes anything. Weather is the smaller swirls in the dynamic fluid of our atmosphere. Climate is the larger swirls that seem more consistent due to their size and longevity. If we can't predict the small swirls (ask any meteorologist) which constitute the large ones, then we can't conceivably predict the large ones either (so there goes our ability to predict whether anthropogenic climate change is a benefit or a detriment).

Nature is genuinely chaotic, and we are a part of the big chaos stew, not detached observers. I wholeheartedly agree that more people need to understand this.
